ce:section.ce:para:
Herein, we reported, for the first time, the ROS generation from narrow bandgap Ti3C2Tx NSs under US irradiation for deep-tissue cancer treatment. We further fabricated 0D/2D hybrid heterojunctions (HJs) by decorating 0D carbon dots (CDs) onto the 2D Ti3C2Tx NSs to enhance the ROS generation efficiency of Ti3C2Tx NSs since the formation of HJs could promote carrier transfer and prevent electron-hole recombination (Scheme 1
                     ). As expected, the designed CD@Ti3C2Tx HJs showed remarkably enhanced ROS generation efficiency, achieving high rate constant (0.166 min−1) for 1,3-diphenylisobenzofuran (DPBF) oxidation by 1O2, which was 2.37- and 3.07-times higher than that of Ti3C2Tx NSs (0.070 min−1) and commercial TiO2 nanoparticles (0.054 min−1), respectively. We also explored the NIR-II photothermal performance of the HJs, and found that the photothermal conversion efficiency at 1064 nm (η

                        1064
                     ) of CD@Ti3C2Tx (64.5%) is significantly higher than that of pristine CDs (49.6%) and Ti3C2Tx (40.1%). Since mild photothermal effects can alleviate tumor hypoxia in the “cold” TME by enhancing intratumor blood flow and improving oxygen supply [5,40,41], we thus sensitized tumors to high tissue-penetrating SDT under additional NIR-II laser in the presence of CD@Ti3C2Tx HJs. Both in vitro and in vivo therapeutic results showed that the complete tumor ablation was realized by synergistically enhanced photothermal-sonodynamic therapy of CD@Ti3C2Tx HJs under NIR-II laser and US irradiation.
